xwpe has been continuously available since 1993 --- over 30 years.
This chapter traces its journey from a student project in Berlin to
a rescued open-source project maintained on Codeberg.

@section Fred Kruse (1991--1997)

@cindex Technical University of Berlin
@cindex Borland Turbo C

Fred Kruse wrote xwpe at the Technical University of Berlin
(@code{fkr@@cs.tu-berlin.de}, later @code{kruse@@rrzn.uni-hannover.de}).
The user interface was modelled after Borland's Turbo C and Turbo Pascal
family, which were the dominant PC development environments of the era.

Kruse released xwpe as free software under the GNU General Public License
version 2.  His last official release was version 1.4.2 (circa 1997).
After that, he went silent --- email to his known addresses bounced, and
no further contact has been established.

The original xwpe supported:
@itemize @bullet
@item Terminal display via curses or termcap.
@item Syntax highlighting for C, C++, Fortran, and Pascal.
@item Integration with gcc, gdb, sdb, and dbx.
@item A project file format for multi-file builds.
@item Mouse support on the Linux console.
@item A DOS/DJGPP port (now removed).
@item German and English documentation.
@end itemize

In 1998, Miroslav Jani@v{s} published the earliest known non-English
review of xwpe in the Czech magazine @cite{Linuxov@'e noviny} (issue
6/1998).  He described xwpe as ``an almost perfect copy of Borland's
interface'' and noted that xwpe passed @code{-c} to all compilers
including @LaTeX{} --- a bug we finally fixed in v1.6.2, 28 years later.

@section Dennis Payne and xwpe-alpha (2000--2006)

@cindex xwpe-alpha
@cindex identicalsoftware.com

Dennis Payne (@code{dulsi@@identicalsoftware.com}) at Rensselaer
Polytechnic Institute picked up xwpe around 2000.  He renamed the
continuation ``xwpe-alpha'' and bumped the version to 1.5.x to
distinguish it from Kruse's releases.

Payne's contributions over six years included:
@itemize @bullet
@item X11 window support (@command{xwpe}, @command{xwe}).
@item GPM mouse integration for terminal mode.
@item autoconf-based build system.
@item X Selection (clipboard) support.
@item Removal of DOS/DJGPP code and other dead paths.
@item Ncurses support (replacing raw termcap).
@item Numerous bug fixes from mailing list reports.
@end itemize

The xwpe-alpha mailing list at @code{identicalsoftware.com} ran from
1998 to 2003 and accumulated 487 messages from dozens of contributors.
These emails remain the richest source of real-world xwpe usage
documentation.  The archive is preserved in the companion repository
@code{xwpe-archive}.

